                var divsize = document.querySelector('#emp-b7db2').parentNode.clientWidth;
                var AdButler = AdButler || {}; AdButler.ads = AdButler.ads || [];
                var abkw = window.abkw || '';
                console.log("emp-b7db2-size-"+divsize);
                if(divsize >= 728){
                    var plc560485 = window.plc560485 || 0;
                    document.write('<'+'div id="placement_560485_'+plc560485+'"></'+'div>');
                    AdButler.ads.push({handler: function(opt){ AdButler.register(181918, 560485, [728,90], 'placement_560485_'+opt.place, opt); }, opt: { pid: rnd, rnd: rnd ,place: plc560485++, keywords: abkw, domain: 'ads.empowerlocal.co', click:'CLICK_MACRO_PLACEHOLDER' }});
                } else{
                    var plc560479 = window.plc560479 || 0;
                    document.write('<'+'div id="placement_560479_'+plc560479+'"></'+'div>');
                    AdButler.ads.push({handler: function(opt){ AdButler.register(181918, 560479, [300,250], 'placement_560479_'+opt.place, opt); }, opt: { pid: rnd, rnd: rnd ,place: plc560479++, keywords: abkw, domain: 'ads.empowerlocal.co', click:'CLICK_MACRO_PLACEHOLDER' }});
                }
                </script></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In an interview with the Bronx Times, he recounted the gruesome details of a harrowing attack on a cold January night in 2016. </span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“Then he sliced me and then he stabbed me again in the stomach and then I grabbed his knife and he sliced my whole arm,” De Marcos Garcia added.<br />
</span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bloody and beaten, De Marcos Garcia walked home to his apartment in Washington Heights, his arm hanging from its socket. His distraught wife called 911 and he was transported to Harlem hospital where he received emergency surgery for his seven stab wounds. </span></p><div id="emp-449bd" class="amp-action" style="text-align:center;">    
                        <script type="text/javascript">
                            var divsize = document.querySelector('#emp-449bd').parentNode.clientWidth;
                            var rnd = Math.floor(Math.random()*10e6);
                            var pid560475 = rnd;
                            var plc560475 = window.plc560475 || 0;
                            var abkw = window.abkw || '';
                            var absrc = 'https://ads.empowerlocal.co/adserve/;ID=181918;size=0x0;setID=560475;type=js;sw='+screen.width+';sh='+screen.height+';spr='+window.devicePixelRatio+';kw='+abkw+';pid='+pid560475+';place='+(plc560475++)+';rnd='+rnd+';click=CLICK_MACRO_PLACEHOLDER';
                            var _absrc = absrc.split("type=js"); absrc = _absrc[0] + 'type=js;referrer=' + encodeURIComponent(document.location.href) + _absrc[1];
                            document.write('<scr'+'ipt src="'+absrc+'" type="text/javascript"></'+'script>');
                        </script></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“My hand didn’t work for about four months,” he said as he opened and closed his fist, recalling a time when that seemingly simple gesture wasn’t so simple. Nonetheless, Garcia could not be kept from work and did what he could with his other hand, for time is money and opening your own restaurant doesn’t come cheap. </span></p>
<figure id="attachment_103660" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-103660" style="max-width: 700px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-103660" src="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?w=700" alt="" width="700" height="452" srcset="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg 3120w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=700,452 700w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=768,496 768w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=1200,774 1200w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=1536,991 1536w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=384,248 384w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=900,581 900w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=1600,1032 1600w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_margguac1.jpg?resize=50,32 50w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-103660" class="wp-caption-text"><span class="image-caption">Cinco de Mayo is more than chips and margaritas &#8212; an homage to the workers behind your favorite Mexican restaurants.</span><span class="image-credit">Photo ET Rodriguez</span></figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Garcia’s dreams of owning his own place stem from his days in Guerrero, Mexico, where work was scarce and eating chicken was something people only did on holidays. In 1998, Garcia decided he was going to cross the border into the U.S. for a better life. He kissed his wife goodbye with promises of finding them a new home and entered the U.S. via professional human traffickers known as </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">coyotes</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">On about the fourth day of his journey, Garcia was separated from his pack. He looked across the desert, but only saw darkness. He had no choice but to wait until daylight and buried himself in the sand to keep away from the scorpions and snakes. By morning, he was reunited and the group was on their way. After a week-long journey, Garcia arrived to NYC where he was bedridden for a week. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“My toenails fell off and I couldn’t walk,” Garcia told the Bronx Times. </span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In Harlem, he shared a one-bedroom apartment with 16 other men where most slept on the floor. </span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“I even had mice eat my nails,” Garcia exclaimed. “I swear to you.” </span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Despite the seemingly horrid living conditions, Garcia had a vision he would not soon abandon. He was committed to sharing his passion for food and hospitality with the people of New York City. His wife, Maribel Pablo Madrigal, originally from Michoacán, later joined him in 2001. She, too, arrived via coyote and experienced her own hardships along the way. The two scrimped and saved working toward the dream of being their own bosses. </span></p>
<figure id="attachment_103661" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-103661" style="max-width: 700px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-103661" src="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?w=700" alt="" width="700" height="493" srcset="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg 2768w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=700,493 700w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=768,541 768w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=1200,845 1200w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=1536,1082 1536w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=384,270 384w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=900,634 900w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=1600,1127 1600w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_manwithmarg.jpg?resize=50,35 50w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-103661" class="wp-caption-text"><span class="image-caption">A crowd of people quickly formed at Cantina Tarasca on Friday, May 3 and everyone had a margarita in hand.</span><span class="image-credit">Photo ET Rodriguez</span></figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2010, Garcia left his job as a waiter at a steakhouse to become a porter at El Porton Mexican restaurant in Harlem. Normally one doesn’t leave a place of work for a demotion at another, but Garcia knew the owner and thought there could be a lot to learn under his employment.  </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A year later, an opportunity to expand the El Porton name arose. This was it — his dream come true. Garcia, his boss and Alejandro Mendoza, whom Garcia had never met, became partners. Garcia gave him almost $40,000, but didn’t sign any paperwork, as he didn’t have a social security number at the time. But Mendoza was up to no good and ran off with Garcia’s money. Garcia’s boss tracked down the thief, but by then, the money was gone and taking Mendoza to court was futile.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The restaurant expanded regardless, just not with Garcia as co-owner, but his boss saw his worth and brought him on as general manager. Garcia worked like the &#8220;Little Engine That Could&#8221; with one goal in mind – to open his own place. He did whatever was asked — if he had to cook, he’d cook; if he had to do deliveries, he’d do deliveries. Things were looking up for Garcia.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Last year, Garcia found a partner and was finally going to have his own restaurant. He approached his boss of more than a decade, thanked him for the work and put in his two-week notice. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“Why are you leaving?” &#8220;Garcia&#8217;s boss cheekily asked. “I was going to sell it to you.”</span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Garcia was giddy with disbelief and this past December, it became official.</span>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“I was saving money to buy [a restaurant], but I never thought it was going to be this one,” Garcia said with a joyful chuckle while standing in the new Cantina Tarasca, formerly El Porton.</span></p>
<figure id="attachment_103666" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-103666" style="max-width: 700px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-103666" src="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?w=700" alt="" width="700" height="499" srcset="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg 2768w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=700,499 700w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=768,547 768w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=1200,855 1200w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=1536,1095 1536w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=384,274 384w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=900,642 900w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=1600,1140 1600w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_flyer.jpg?resize=50,36 50w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-103666" class="wp-caption-text"><span class="image-caption">A flyer advertises free tequila shots for Cinco de Mayo at Cantina Tarasca at 576 Southern Blvd.</span><span class="image-credit">Photo ET Rodriguez</span></figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Under his new ownership, the restaurant has adapted a theme of Guerrero and Michoacán, Mexico, the hometowns of Garcia and his wife, respectively and the two are dedicated to quality ingredients and service with a smile. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“You can come here with your family or you can come here by yourself. Everybody&#8217;s friendly. The staff is friendly. The drinks are good. The food is good,” said Jose Galarza, who has been visiting the restaurant for four years although he lives on the other side of the Bronx in Parkchester. “And I noticed that the menu just got bigger.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">New additions include gorditas, churros, and the trending birria, where marinated beef ribs, shoulder and brisket are simmered in a pot filled with aromatics and chiles until the meat is tender enough to be shredded with a fork and served however you like. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Drinks have always been a favorite of Garcia’s to experiment with. The new chipotle mezcal margarita is smokey on two levels, and balanced with the sweetness of <em>panela</em> sugar with a homemade <em>chamoy</em> and <em>tajin</em> garnish on the rim. You can also get your margaritas frozen with a range of flavors including the recently added prickly pear.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Garcia has yet to give himself a paycheck or a day off as he lives to make the restaurant the best it can be. His joy is in creating new menu items, getting to the market early and importing rare mezcals from Mexico. </span></p>
<figure id="attachment_103664" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-103664" style="max-width: 715px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class=" wp-image-103664" src="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_sombreros.jpeg?w=512" alt="" width="715" height="476" srcset="https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_sombreros.jpeg 512w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_sombreros.jpeg?resize=384,256 384w, https://www.bxtimes.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/cincodemayo_sombreros.jpeg?resize=50,33 50w" sizes="(max-width: 715px) 100vw, 715px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-103664" class="wp-caption-text"><span class="image-caption">Sombreros hang in one of the hundreds of Mexican businesses sprawled across the Bronx.</span><span class="image-credit">Photo ET Rodriguez</span></figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Stories like Garcia&#8217;s are but one of many. For decades, Mexicans have been migrating to the U.S., making them the No. 1 Hispanic demographic in the country and <a href="https://www.nyc.gov/assets/immigrants/downloads/pdf/Hispanic-Immigrant-Fact-Sheet.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">No. 2 in the Bronx</a>, superseding the once dominant Puerto Ricans of the borough. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">And while people may spew racist rhetoric, how many of them know about the Mexican-American War (1846-48), in which Mexicans fought to regain their land (modern-day Texas)? Or about the Gadsden Purchase of 1854 that turned parts of Mexico into New Mexico and Arizona? Do they know about </span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Operation-Wetback" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Operation Wetback</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> in 1954, implemented to stop the influx of undocumented migrants into the U.S. from Mexico, while the U.S. was simultaneously operating the Mexican Farm Labor Program also known as the </span><a href="https://guides.loc.gov/latinx-civil-rights/bracero-program#:~:text=An%20executive%20order%20called%20the,on%20short%2Dterm%20labor%20contracts." target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bracero Program</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> from 1942 to 1964? The history of </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mexicans in the U.S. is fraught with contradictions, abuse and exploitation. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Despite his struggle, Garcia has always been gracious. His daughter, 24, graduated with a degree in business from Baruch College and his son, 22, works at the restaurant with him — and the pride shines in his eyes. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“If you come with a purpose, it’s worth it, because suffering is temporary,” he said. “It’s part of the process and the success.”</span>
<hr />
<p><i>Reach ET Rodriguez at </i><a href="mailto:etrodriguez317@gmail.com"><i>etrodriguez317@gmail.com</i></a><i>. For more coverage, follow us on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram @bronxtime</i></p>
